Wall St. from Broad St.

1825

Photo by Brown Brothers
220 West 42nd St.
New York City

Wall Street, east from a point to the east of Broad Street. In the right center is the distinctive Merchants Exchange. This occupies the entire block frontage from William to Hanover Street's. It is later to become the U. S. Custom House. On their removal to the new Custom House at Bowling Green, the National City Bank will take over. Note the scaffold suspended at the corner.

About 1860

Gift of Urbrock Collection

Wall Street, south side, east from Broad Street. At the left is the old Custom House that originally was the Merchants Exchange. It is later to be occupied by the National City Bank. On the right margin are the buildings that were re-moved for the ornate Drexel Morgan & Co. Bldg of 1872.

About 1864

Gift of Urbrock Collection

Wall Street, at the S. E. corner of Broad Street, showing the site of the Drexel Morgan & Co. Bldg. of 1872 prior to the improvement. Wall Street is on the left, while Broad Street is on the right. Incidently the Mills Bldg. was erected on the latter thoroughfare adjacent to the aforementioned structure.

About 1866

Gift of Urbrook Collection

Wall Street, west across Broad & Nassau Streets, to Broadway. At the latter point appears the dominant (then) feature, Trinity Church. at the right margin are the steps of the U. S. Sub Treasury prior to the erection of the Washington statue there in 1883. Beyond same is a five story building at the N. W. corner of Nassau Street. This was increased two stories in height and became the Manhattan Trust Co. The structure on the left center housing "Kiernan's" is the predecessor of the Wilks Building.

Between 1872-80

Gift of Ubrock Collection

(1)
Wall Street, west across Broad & Nassau Street's, to Broadway. At the latter point is the dominant Trinity Church. The four corners in the center are occupied by, the Drexel Morgan Bldg, the Kiernan Telegraphic Agency, the 5 story (later 7) structure soon to be the Manhattan Trust Co. home and the U. S. Sub Treasury. Note the absence of the Washington statue on the steps of the latter.

Between 1872-80

(2)

Wall Street and at the head of Street may be seen the spires of Trinity Church. At the right of picture may be seen the Sub-Treasury Building, East Side, and the statue of George Washington, corner of Wall street and Nassau.

No date, nor record.

Wall Street, west from Broad & Nassau Streets, to Broadway, showing at the latter point, Trinity Church. New Street intersects at the left. Note the absence of the National Bank of the Republic (Fort Sherman) that was erected in 1880 at the N.E. corner of Broadway. A comparison with other views leads the writer to conclude that this photo dates between 1872-1880.

Between 1872-1880

American Studio, photo

Photograph by Brown Brothers
220 West 42nd St.
New York City

1875

Wall Street (right), at and adjoining the N. E. corner of Nassau Street (left), showing the U. S. Subtreasury and it's adjacent Assay Office. The latter was removed in 1916 and reconstructed in the American wing of the Metropolitan Museum of Art. On the left margin appears the 5 story Mechanics & Metals National Bank, occupying the Nassau Street frontage from Pine to Cedar Street's. This structure was subsequently replaced with the modern Chase National Bank Building. Note the absence of the J. Q. A. Ward statue of Washington on the steps of the Sub Treasury. This work of art was unveiled November 26, 1883, the day following Evacuation Day.

Prior to 1883

Gift of Urbrock Collection

Old Sub-Treasury building situated at Wall and Nassau Streets, New York City. In front the steps to building are broken by pedistal on which is erected Ward's hero sized bronze statue of George Washington. The statue was unveiled November 26, 1883, following evacuation Day. On the same site, Washington took his oath of office as the President of the United States. April 30, 1789.

old Sub-Treasury building situated at Wall and Nassau Streets, New York City. In front the steps to building are broken by pedistal on which is erected Ward's hero sized bronze statue of George Washington. The statue was unveiled November 26, 1883, following evacuation Day. On the same site, Washington took his oath of office as the President of the United States. April 30, 1789.

Wall Street, at the N. E. corner of Nassau Street, showing the U. S. Sub-treasury with it's J.Q.A. Ward statue of Washington (unveiled November 26, 1883). This enlargement from an original lantern slide has been reversed; Nassau Street that appears on the right should be at the left, where the Drexel, Morgan & Co. Bldg. and the U.S. Assay Office are.

About 1885

Gift of Russell Freeman
New York Public Library

Broad Street, west side, south from, but not including Wall Street. Building shown on the extreme right, is the old N.Y. Stock Exchange. The building with the tower, is the N.Y. Produce Exchange.

About 1885.

New York Edison Co.

Broad Street, west side, south from, but not including Wall, to, but not including Beaver Streets. Building shown on the extreme right, is the old Stock Exchange. In the background appears the tower of the N.Y. Produce Exchange.

About 1885.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

8-60 Broad Street, west side, from south of Wall Street to north of Beaver Street, At the right, with the columns, is the old Stock Exchange. In the left background is the tower of the recently built Produce Exchange.

1885.

Wall and Nassau Streets, showing Sub Treasury Buildings to the right may be seen the U.S. Assay office.

Langill, Photo.

1885.

Broad Street, south from Wall Street, showing mainly the westerly side of this thoroughfare. To the left, center, and right respectively are, the old Mills Building (replaced in 1926 by the 38-story Equitable Trust Co. Building), the Produce Exchange (distinctive tower atop) and the New York Stock Exchange Building. Adjoining the latter is the renovated 6-story building adjoining the corner structure. These were subsequently demolished and their site improved by a larger building and which in time was replaced by the north wing of the Stock Exchange.

See King's Handbook of New York (1893), page 155 for a slightly later view.

Between 1889-1893

Gift Thru New York Historical Society

No's. 6 and 8-10 Broad Street, adjoining and south of the S.W. corner of Wall Street, and showing prominently the New York Stock Exchange Building of an early period.

1889

Gift of Urbrock Collection

Wall Street, south side, west and across Broad Street (left), as photographed from the Sub Treasury steps. The frontage referred to is in the center and extends from Broad Street on the left to New Street. The latter thoroughfare is behind the Washington statue. Note the Mortimer Building there. A glimpse of Trinity Church on Broadway appears behind the statue. Under demolition are the corner structures to provide a site for the new Wilks Building. Eventually all of these buildings will vanish for the ever expanding New York Stock Exchange.

About 1890

Gift of Urbrock Collection

Wall Street, west across Nassau Street, showing prominently the J. Q. A. Ward statue of Washington on the U.S. Sub Treasury steps • To the left center is Trinity Church at Broadway. Between these features appear the dark National Bank of the Republic and the white marble Manhattan Trust Co. home. The newly erected Mortimer Bldg. is at the left margin at New Street.

1890

Gift of Urbrock Collection

Broad Street, south from Wall Street, showing prominently the westerly side of this important thoroughfare.

At the extreme right is the Wilks Building separated from the New York Stock Exchange Building by a renovated (between 1889-1893) five-story structure. Towering above same is the graceful Mackey Building. The Johnston Building is to the south, while beyond appears the dim outline of the Produce Exchange. Note between these the Edison Building.

At the left margin is the Drexel Building and its adjoining Mills structure.

About 1893

Gift of Urbrock Collection

Broad Street, west side, south from but not including Wall, to, but not including Beaver Streets. Also shown is the S.E. corner of Wall and Broad Streets, which is occupied by Drexel, Morgan and Co.

About 1893.

P. L. Sperr.
(Taken by August Loeffler)

Broad Street, at, adjoining and south of the S.W. corner of Wall Street. Also shown is the Drexel, Morgan and Company Building, on the S.E. corner of Broad and Wall Streets.

About 1894.

Brown Brothers.

Wall Street, west from, and including Broad Street, to and including Broadway, showing the front view of Trinity Church.

Ewing Galloway.

SEE - JOHNSTON VIEW of which this is a
copy & enlargement.

Wall Street, west across Broad (left) and Nassau (right) Street's, to Broadway, showing the westerly extremity of this financial thoroughfare headed by Trinity Church. At the four corners in the foreground are, the Drexel Morgan & Co. Building, the Wilks Building, the Manhattan Trust Co. Building and the U. S. Sub Treasury. Adjoining the latter is the old Assay Office. To the right of the Church is the darkened National Bank of the Republic popularly known
as "Fort Sherman".
1894

Nea. ~2403

General view northward of lower Manhattan, photographed from the Produce Exchange (according to belief of the writer). Through the center is Broad Street with its Sub Treasury at Wall Street. To the left are New Street and Broadway. Upon the latter, are the outstanding 17-story Manhattan Life Building and the 21-story American Surity Building. Under construction in the midground is the 17-story Johnston Building. To the right is the massive Mills Building.

About 1895

Ewing Galloway

title: General view - Lower Manhattan.

text:
Broad Street, west side, south from Wall Street. At the left and right margins respectively are; the Drexel, Morgan & Co. Bldg. and the New York Stock Exchange. Two doors beyond the latter is Commercial Cable (Mackey) Bldg. under construction. Separating this and the Johnston Bldg. are two small structures on this side of Exchange Place. These will shortly provide the site for the Blair Bldg. This photo is an enlargement from an original lantern slide.

Circa 1896

Wall Street, at the N. E. corner of Nassau Street, showing the U. S. Sub Treasury steps and the J. Q. A. Ward statue of Washington thereupon. The inscription reads "Erected By Voluntary Subscription Under The Auspices Of The Chamber Of Commerce Of The State Of New York, November 26, 1883."  About 1900  Gift of Urbrock Collection

Wall Street, at the N. E. corner of Nassau Street, showing the U. S. Sub Treasury and the J. Q. A. Ward statue of Washington.

About 1900

Gift of Urbrock Collection

Wall Street, north side, at Nassau Street, showing progressively (from the right) the old U. S. Assay Office, the U. S. Sub Treasury and the Manhattan Trust Co. bldg. Towering over the latter is the American Surety Building that was erected between 1893-7 at Broadway and Pine St.

About 1900

Gift of Urbrock Collection

Broad Street, adjoining the S.W. corner of Wall Street, showing the facade of the New York Stock Exchange Building.

The center figure represents "Integrity." On the right the groups represent "Primitive Agriculture and the Products of the Soil" and "Mining." On the left, "Motive Power, Scientific and Mechanical Appliances" and "the Designer and Mechanic."

This appeared in the Evening Mail Illustrated Saturday Magazine of June 18, 1904 several days after the unveiling ceremonies.

September 30, 1909

H. N. Tiemann, photo
Gift of Urbrock Collection

Wall Street, at the S. E. corner of Broad Street, showing the Drexel Morgan Building.  This structure was demolished and replaced in 1912-3.  To the left is the 25 story Equitable Trust Co. Bldg. (No. 37-43 Wall Street) that later will erect a 38 story structure to replace the 10 story Mills Building (No. 11-23 Broad Street).  The latter appears on the right at Exchange Place, and adjoins the Morgan feature.

About 1910

Gift ofUrbrock Collection

Wall Street, at the N.W. corner of Nassau Street, showing under demolition at that location, the Gillenden Building. This was replaced by the 32 story Bankers Trust Company Building. This property is reported to have brought one of the highest prices in New York real estate dealings, $825 per square foot. The writer believes that the vantage point for the photographer is atop the former Schmerhorn Building on Broadway and that he is viewing southeastward.

April 28, 1910

Gift of Albert A. Volk Company
A. R. Bond
Irving Underhill
Wall Street, North West corner and Nassau Street, showing the Gillender Building demolished on May 1st, 1910. About 1910. No record of Photographer.

Nassau Street, west side, from Wall (left) to Pine (right) Streets, showing the new Bankers Trust Building and the adjoining Hanover National Bank Building. The latter is at the S. W. corner of Nassau and Pine Streets. This site, in conjunction with the Astor Building (left margin) was absorbed into the later enlarged Bankers Trust Building.
Note the Singer Tower at the right.

1911

Gift of Ubrock Collection

Wall Street, south side, east from Broad Street.
About 1912.
Ewing Galloway.

Wall Street (left) east from Broad (right) to Hanover Streets, showing the structure at the S.E. corner of the first point under demolition. J. P. Morgan and Co. occupy a 4-story structure at this location today (1938). On the right appears the east side of Broad Street, south to and including Exchange Place with the 10-story Mills Building (now the site of the 38-story Equitable Trust Co. Building) at the N.E. corner of the latter point. Across the Place and at its S.E. corner is the 21-story Broad Exchange Building. On the extreme left appears the United States Sub-Treasury Building. This set consists of a negative and a positive.

May 12, 1913.

Gift of Albert A. Volk Co.

30-32 Wall Street, adjoining the N.E. corner of Nassau Street, showing the old United States Assay Office Building under demolition. Upon this site was erected a 4-story structure. The stone facade of this building, the oldest on Wall Street is now in the American Wing of the Metropolitan Museum of Art. It was the work of Robert de Forest.

1916.

F. M. Demarest.
Gift of Albert A. Volk Co.

Wall Street, adjoining the N. E. corner of Nassau Street, showing the old U. S. Assay Office occupying this site. It was demolished in 1916 and portions removed to the American wing of the Metropolitan Museum of Art. The Bank of Manhattan Building includes this location today. A new Assay Office building was erected at South Street and Old Slip.

Prior to 1916

Gift of Urbrock Collection

Wall Street, adjoining the N. E. corner of Nassau Street, showing the old U. S. Assay Office occupying this site. It was demolished in 1916 and portions removed to the American wing of the Metropolitan Museum of Art. A new building housing the Assay Office was erected on South Street, at Old Slip.

Prior to 1916

Gift of Urbrock Collection

Wall Street, north side, west across Nassau Street, showing prominently a Liberty Loan Drive at the U. S. Sub Treasury steps. Broadway is to the left, where a glimpse of Trinity Church appears. The vacant plot on the right was the site of the old U. S. Assay Office.

The dark building in the centre is the 17-story Johnston Building, which will be replaced in 1931 by the 48-story Continental Bank Trust Company Building. Immediately beyond it is the Ocean Cable Offices Building and beyond this is the building of the Wall Street Journal.

Wall Street (center of No. 1) and vicinity, at Broad and Nassau Streets, as viewed westward from the Wall and Hanover (Brown Bros.) Bldg. Prominently shown is the 32 storied Bankers Trust Co; at the N.W. corner of Wall and Nassau Streets. Adjoining same on the latter front is the 22 story Hanover-National Bank Bldg. To the right of the latter in View No. 2 appears the 38 storied Equitable Bldg. on Broadway. At the margin is the Bank of N.Y. and Trust Co. with a golden eagle atop thereof. The interviewing space between this and the aforementioned Bankers Trust Co. Bldg. will shortly provide a base for the 70 storied Bank of Manhattan.

The "Akron;" a United States Navy airship sailing over the financial area in lower Manhattan. Directly beneath same is the pinnacle of the huge 60 Wall Street Tower. The octangular structure appearing on the left is the City Bank, Farmers Trust Company Building. Photographers vantage point is No. 415 Broad Street, viewing northward. This set consists of 2 views; No. 2 including the Bank of Manhattan Building.

November 2, 1931.

NERVOUS CENTER OF AMERICAN BUSINESS - BROAD AND WALL STREET
New York Stock Exchange at right and doorway of J. P. Morgan & Co. at left.

WHEN THE MARKET BROKE IN RECORD PANIC--CROWDS GATHER AT SUB TREASURY TO WATCH MOBS SURGE ABOUT STOCK EXCHANGE ACROSS THE STREET

NEW YORK.--PHOTO SHOWS: An exciting moment during the break of the market in the record panic when nearly 13,000,000 shares were traded. Here the crowds are gathered at the Sub Treasury, watching the excitement of still another crowd at the Stock Exchange, across the corner--at Broad and Wall Streets.

WALL STREET CROWD.
